{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":5028,"record_hash":"sha256:bd536ac7dc99b0899a1e2a11ffe65aaf10ce756b6fd5e68f68fd6c7a9096017c","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:16:33.929Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:225-232) [added]\n[P2] Git hash labels can preserve affixed secrets\n\n`is_git_object_id()` preserves the whole candidate when it finds a labelled 40/64-hex subrange. Since `-`, `/`, and `=` are candidate bytes and accepted hash boundaries, a value like `commit <sha>-<random-secret>` can be treated as a Git object ID even though the random suffix is stored too. Require the candidate to end at the hash, or otherwise preserve only the hash-shaped part.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:110-116) [added]\n[P2] UUID-shaped secrets can bypass redaction\n\nUUID-ish values are preserved before considering field context, so a UUID-shaped secret under `api_key`, `token`, or `secret` would be stored verbatim. A small fix would let sensitive field names override the UUID/timestamp allowlist, or only preserve UUIDs for known ID-like fields.\n\n## Finding 3 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:119-123) [added]\n[P3] Slash-inclusive candidates can over-redact paths\n\nIncluding `/` in candidate bytes catches slashy base64, but it also makes long paths scan as one candidate. Some realistic path strings can cross the entropy threshold and lose useful transcript context. This may be an acceptable POC tradeoff, but it is still worth knowing about.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nlets fix Slash-inclusive candidates can over-redact paths\nAnd also for Git hash labels can preserve affixed secrets we can take the approach to preserve only the hash-shaped part. Maybe we do something like this for UUIDs as well\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:16:33.929Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:225-232) [added]\n[P2] Git hash labels can preserve affixed secrets\n\n`is_git_object_id()` preserves the whole candidate when it finds a labelled 40/64-hex subrange. Since `-`, `/`, and `=` are candidate bytes and accepted hash boundaries, a value like `commit <sha>-<random-secret>` can be treated as a Git object ID even though the random suffix is stored too. Require the candidate to end at the hash, or otherwise preserve only the hash-shaped part.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:110-116) [added]\n[P2] UUID-shaped secrets can bypass redaction\n\nUUID-ish values are preserved before considering field context, so a UUID-shaped secret under `api_key`, `token`, or `secret` would be stored verbatim. A small fix would let sensitive field names override the UUID/timestamp allowlist, or only preserve UUIDs for known ID-like fields.\n\n## Finding 3 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:119-123) [added]\n[P3] Slash-inclusive candidates can over-redact paths\n\nIncluding `/` in candidate bytes catches slashy base64, but it also makes long paths scan as one candidate. Some realistic path strings can cross the entropy threshold and lose useful transcript context. This may be an acceptable POC tradeoff, but it is still worth knowing about.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nlets fix Slash-inclusive candidates can over-redact paths\nAnd also for Git hash labels can preserve affixed secrets we can take the approach to preserve only the hash-shaped part. Maybe we do something like this for UUIDs as well\n"}]}}}